prefix: Approach the following question the way someone in high school would.
problem_prompt:
Approach the following question the way someone in high school would. The values of a function $f(x)$ are given below:

\begin{tabular}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\ \hline $f(x)$ & 10 & 17 & 26 & 37 & 50 \\ \hline \end{tabular}Evaluate $f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)$.
gpt_response:
To find $f^{-1}(50)$, we look for when $f(x) = 50$. We see that $f(7) = 50$, so $f^{-1}(50) = 7$.

To find $f^{-1}(10)$, we look for when $f(x) = 10$. We see that $f(3) = 10$, so $f^{-1}(10) = 3$.

To find $f^{-1}(26)$, we look for when $f(x) = 26$. We see that $f(5) = 26$, so $f^{-1}(26) = 5$.

Now we substitute these values into the given expression: $f^{-1}(7 \times 3 + 5) = f^{-1}(21 + 5) = f^{-1}(26)$.

Looking at the table, we see that $f(5) = 26$, so the answer is $\boxed{5}$.
